article.description:
Ashley Augspurger scored 18 points,
all on 3-pointers, and Joy Jenkins banked in a 3-pointer with 41
seconds left as Colorado State (No. 21 ESPN/USA Today; No. 20 Associated Press) beat Nevada-Las Vegas 62-57 Saturday.
article.headline: Rams hit late free throws to stop UNLV
article.linkText: No. 21 Colorado State wins with a 3-pointer off the bank
article.story:
FORT COLLINS, Colo. (AP) -- Banking in a 3-pointer with 41
seconds left wasn't exactly the way Colorado State coach Tom Collen
planned to win the game Saturday against Nevada-Las Vegas.

	   He'll take it, even if he did feel a bit sheepish afterward.

	   Sophomore Joy Jenkins made the 3-pointer off the glass to help Colorado State (No. 21 ESPN/USA Today; No. 20 Associated Press) prevail 62-57.

	   Freshman Ashley Venekamp and Angie Gorton each hit two free
throws in the waning seconds as Colorado State (15-3, 4-0 Mountain
West) held off its main rival in the race for the league title.

	   "We did draw that play up, yeah," Collen said with a laugh.
"We wanted Joy to take the 3, but we didn't ask her to call `bank'
on it.

	   "I'm sure that was very frustrating to Regina (UNLV coach
Regina Miller). If somebody banked in a 3 to win a game against us,
I'd be frustrated, too."

	   Jenkins said she knew her shot was long. "I kind of forced it
up a little bit," she said. "But that's all right, it went in."

	   Teammate Ashley Augspurger added, "That's what the backboard is
there for."

	   Augspurger scored 18 points, all on 3-pointers, as the Rams
posted their fifth consecutive victory.

	   Miller admitted it was tough to lose on a 3-pointer off the
glass.

	   "Oh, my gosh," she said. "That was THE basket. I thought when
she first released it that it was going to be short. I never
thought it was going to bank -- maybe go in but never bank off the
glass. Petra Glaser was right there in her face, too.

	   "If we get a stop there, then they have to play catch-up in the
last minute of the game instead of us."

	   UNLV rallied from an 11-point deficit midway through the second
half, taking a 57-55 lead on Constance Jinks' layup -- UNLV's third shot on that possession -- with 1:07 remaining.

	   Jenkins countered with her 3-pointer with 41 seconds left. Jinks
missed a short jumper seconds later, and UNLV fouled Venekamp, who
made both free throws with 15.2 seconds left.

	   After a turnover by Jinks on a bad pass, CSU's Angie Gorton hit
two more foul shots with 4.3 seconds left.

	   Two days earlier, the Rams went 0-for-14 from 3-point range.
With Augspurger leading the way at 6-for-8 on 3-pointers, the Rams
were 12-for-21 against the Lady Rebels.

	   "Ashley Augspurger just killed us on the 3-point shot," Miller
said. "It seemed like any time we gave her any space, she hit
it."

	   After his team failed to hit a 3-pointer for the first time in
232 games, Collen refused to panic.

	   "I'm a shooter's coach," he said. "I let people take shots,
and most importantly I let people miss shots. When you let kids do
that and they don't worry about getting yanked out, good shooters
eventually are going to come back and make shots.

	   "I don't think this team loses confidence in their ability to
shoot the 3."

	   Linda Frohlich had 14 of her 18 points in the second half and
finished with 12 rebounds for UNLV (14-3, 2-2), which was 0-for-12
on 3-pointers.

	   Gorton had 13 points and 10 rebounds for the Rams, and Jenkins
had 12 points.

	   Jinks had 17 points on 8-for-24 shooting.

	   Collen also praised the play of Venekamp, who drew the defensive
assignment on Jinks after Jenkins' go-ahead basket.

	   "When it came down to needing a stop, I felt like Ashley had
done the best job of defending Jinks and making her take bad
shots," Collen said. "The key to guarding Jinks is to not bite on
her 10,000 head fakes.

	   "It's a tribute to her, a freshman in a pressure situation,
guarding the kid that we knew was going to take the shot. Then she
stepped to the line and made her free throws, too."
